SUMMARY:Her Smoke Rose Up Forever - James Tiptree Jr.
DESCRIPTION:The Sci Fi Book Club\nHi all\,\n\nFor May\, we will be reading
  another short story collection. Following April’s selection\, *Best Ame
 rican Science Fiction and Fantasy 2025*\, we’ll turn to an older antholo
 gy. This collection features stories by a science fiction writer who remai
 ned cloaked in mystery for years.\n\nBook of the Month\n*Her Smoke Rose Up
  Forever* \\- James Tiptree Jr\\. \\(1990\\)\n\nDirect from [this amazing 
 Portalist](https://theportalist.com/james-tiptree-jr-enigmatic-author) art
 icle:\n"James Tiptree Jr. left an enduring mark on modern speculative fict
 ion — but she’s perhaps more mysterious and enigmatic today than ever 
 before.\n\nTiptree was one of the pen names used by female sci-fi author A
 lice Bradley Sheldon (née Alice Hastings Bradley). The daughter of prolif
 ic fiction writer Mary Hastings Bradley\, Sheldon may have been born with 
 the gift of words\, but her path to literary success wasn’t clear-cut.\n
 \nAlthough Sheldon is best known for her sci-fi writing\, she had an eclec
 tic and accomplished career. At various times in her life\, Sheldon was a 
 research psychologist\, painter\, art critic\, imagery intelligence operat
 ive\, CIA operative\, and more. In many of these fields\, she was one of t
 he few women in an industry dominated by men. "\n\nGiven this and Tiptree'
 s well-known stories included in this collection\, I don't think we can pa
 ss up this opportunity. As with any other collection we read for Book Club
 \, if a story isn't speaking to you\, go ahead and skip it! There are 18 s
 elections in here\, I'm sure we'll have plenty to discuss.\n\nBelow\, you'
 ll find a few notables and a brief description:\n\n* “The Women Men Don
 ’t See” – A classic feminist sci-fi story exploring gender\, invisib
 ility\, and societal expectations.\n* “Houston\, Houston\, Do You Read?
 ” – A Hugo Award–winning story about time travel\, gender\, and post
 -apocalyptic society.\n* “Love Is the Plan the Plan Is Death” – A hi
 ghly acclaimed story told from the perspective of an alien species\, explo
 ring instinct\, love\, and survival.\n* “The Girl Who Was Plugged In” 
 – A groundbreaking cyberpunk-like story about identity\, media\, and cor
 porate control of bodies.\n* “And I Awoke and Found Me Here on the Cold 
 Hill’s Side” – A dark\, unsettling exploration of obsession and desi
 re for alien contact.\n\nThere are a few printings of this collections. I 
 think [I'm going to pick up this one](https://bookshop.org/p/books/her-smo
 ke-rose-up-forever-james-tiptree/163a6a04d0124023?ean=9781892391209&next=t
 &utm_source=google&utm_medium=cpc&utm_campaign=%7Bcampaignname%7D&utm_cont
 ent=6443417794&gad_source=1&gad_campaignid=16235479093&gbraid=0AAAAACfld43
 fka72FJRQfybRz8siTTDOZ&gclid=Cj0KCQiAprLLBhCMARIsAEDhdPdhUhUk1aiXVGaWtVIu9
 frZcido-IwCeX0rcqajtxQRQLphaxpwy68aAvCqEALw_wcB)\, as it includes some rev
 isions from the author’s original notes.\n\nTo join a Book Club meeting\
 , all you will need is YOURSELF. If you haven’t had a chance to finish t
 he book\, we still would love for you to join us in the discussion.\n\nNot
  able to join us in person for events? [The Sci Fi Book Club is on Discord
 ](https://discord.gg/MM3hNQFW). Join us and keep the conversation going.
